      <hedline>
        <hl1>60 Years of Progress</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from retired New York State Supreme Court Justice Bentley Kassal, commenting on August 11 article, praises selection of Sen Joseph Lieberman as Democratic vice presidential candidate</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>What a difference 60 years makes -- the nomination of a Jew, Joseph I. Lieberman, in the year 2000 to be vice president of the United States (front page, Aug. 11).</p>
        <p>In 1941, after World War II had begun but before this country's entry, I volunteered for service, first to the Office of Naval Intelligence and after that, the F.B.I. I was summarily rejected by both, without any investigation of my credentials.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>What a difference 60 years makes -- the nomination of a Jew, Joseph I. Lieberman, in the year 2000 to be vice president of the United States (front page, Aug. 11).</p>
        <p>In 1941, after World War II had begun but before this country's entry, I volunteered for service, first to the Office of Naval Intelligence and after that, the F.B.I. I was summarily rejected by both, without any investigation of my credentials.</p>
        <p>Later, I learned that it was the policy of J. Edgar Hoover and the naval intelligence office not to accept Jews. So I enlisted in the Army Air Force and served as an intelligence officer overseas for two years. I received the Bronze Star for my service.</p>
        <p>So it is rewarding to see Senator  Lieberman on a national ticket. I hope he will be judged solely on merit.</p>
        <p>BENTLEY KASSAL  New York, Aug. 11, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a retired New York State Supreme Court justice.</p>
      </block>
